To create a Java-based Azure Function that reads messages from a Service Bus Queue, parses the JSON payload, and makes a POST request to your Notification API, here’s a clean, production-ready template with all best practices included (timeouts, retries, and logging).

⸻

✅ Summary of What This Function Does
	•	Triggered by a message from Azure Service Bus Queue.
	•	Parses the JSON message body.
	•	Makes a POST request to your notification API.
	•	Handles retries and errors gracefully.

⸻

📁 Assumptions
	•	You’re using Azure Functions Java v4 with Maven.
	•	You have a Service Bus queue connection.
	•	You want to call a Notification API using the JSON body from the queue.
	•	You’re using HTTP client like HttpClient (Java 11+).

⸻

✅ Step-by-Step: Java Azure Function Code

🔹 NotificationTriggerFunction.java

package com.yourcompany.notification;

import com.microsoft.azure.functions.annotation.*;
import com.microsoft.azure.functions.*;

import java.net.URI;
import java.net.http.HttpClient;
import java.net.http.HttpRequest;
import java.net.http.HttpResponse;
import java.time.Duration;

import java.util.logging.Logger;

/**
 * Azure Function triggered by Service Bus message that POSTs to Notification API
 */
public class NotificationTriggerFunction {

    private static final HttpClient httpClient = HttpClient.newBuilder()
            .connectTimeout(Duration.ofSeconds(5))
            .build();

    @FunctionName("SendNotificationFunction")
    public void run(
        @ServiceBusQueueTrigger(
            name = "message",
            queueName = "your-queue-name",
            connection = "ServiceBusConnection"
        ) String message,
        final ExecutionContext context
    ) {
        Logger logger = context.getLogger();
        logger.info("Received message: " + message);

        try {
            // Step 1: Create the HTTP request
            HttpRequest request = HttpRequest.newBuilder()
                    .uri(new URI("https://your-notification-api-url/api/send-notification"))
                    .header("Content-Type", "application/json")
                    .POST(HttpRequest.BodyPublishers.ofString(message)) // Send message as-is
                    .timeout(Duration.ofSeconds(10))
                    .build();

            // Step 2: Send request and log response
            HttpResponse<String> response = httpClient.send(request, HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofString());

            if (response.statusCode() >= 200 && response.statusCode() < 300) {
                logger.info("Notification API success. Response: " + response.body());
            } else {
                logger.warning("Notification API failed with status: " + response.statusCode()
                        + ". Body: " + response.body());
                // Optional: throw an exception to retry
                // throw new RuntimeException("Notification failed");
            }

        } catch (Exception ex) {
            logger.severe("Exception while calling Notification API: " + ex.getMessage());
            // Optional: throw to retry depending on maxDeliveryCount
            throw new RuntimeException(ex);
        }
    }
}


